Why would the client tell the server how much hate they were generating? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=istari@graffeswizardcompilation>Istari</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/18/03 4:55:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25467.topic&index=74>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> base1</span><hr size=1> Nadair: to my knowledge, Barrier of Force is not a nuke.<br>
<br>
to continue my notion, manaburn ahs 'no' or '1' point of aggro. look at its base1, and it is a nuke. When they broke our aggro, I was one to believe that all of the damage multipliers - crits, focus, manaburn multiplier - were now giving aggro. to substantiate my notion of this being true, I looked to the rain's aggro intersects(with another plot of aggro) and found that it was very close to the base1 of a rain spell.<br>
<br>
This heralds my uncertainty- field tests indicate the aggro of the rains to be 41.6% of what it'd be if the rain aggrod like a normal nuke. That I found the same number(roughly) from different types of tests - tripong, doubled summons, aggro calculated intersects - indicates the methods used were somewhat precise... the base1 is a mystery to me. the base1 of a nuke is its dmg, of course. this is my theory- take it for what you will. common practice indicates that rains produce a greatly lessened amount of aggro... this is only my attempt to explain how much.<br>
<br>
this falls into the camp of aconcs being resisted. we don't have the information about the way the aggro works. I can play my wizard with either opinion in mind, and another shall have no concrete ability to criticize the way I play- only their differing, unsubstantiated opinion. However,  I can lend advice and leave that ultimate choice up to the wizard who is playing. I can play and perfect and what is perfected in game is true to have worked as I intended it, when it is successful. Additionally, I can lend my findings and advice to others. If you choose to trust my method or conjecture, it's your choice. I'll always try to provide you with how I came to the conclusion.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=istari@graffeswizardcompilation>Istari</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 143<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/18/03 8:38:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25467.topic&index=76>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> basically</span><hr size=1> I found four numbers, three which I know, one which I do not:<br>
<br>
single target dd : rain<br>
a/b : x/y<br>
<br>
a = aggro of st dd<br>
b = damage of st dd<br>
x = aggro of rain<br>
y = damage of rain<br>
<br>
if you had done, say, 9k aggro and someone with a rain had 9k aggro with 9kdmg st and 19271 in rains(just arbitrary values), then you'd be able to determine that the ratio if 1:.467. This is what I did in several instances, even using a 3 man ping pong team to find where I'd slightly have more aggro than someone using no focus and st nukes.<br>
<br>
I'd wonder if you had ever used a rain spell at all if you came to the conclusion that it produces full aggro. I already said that I do not know how the mechanics worked for rains. I only took a guess. The whole point of that formula was that I didn't multiply the numerator by the SCS modifier. You didn't catch that. I found a numerical oddity and wondered if it had any significance. If you trust me on that I'm not lying when I used the above method, then you can accept what I'm saying. You can only trust me. You weren't there when I did these tests(and I'm not sure as to the location of the data I wrote down, about 4 pages of it) so I suppose if you make it your intent to distrust what I say, there's no way for me to prove otherwise.<br>
<br>
41 1/3 %<br>
<br>
this is my value that I trust myself on to be close. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#ffffff>- </font><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation>Graffë's Wizard Discussion</a><font color=#ffffff> - </font><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1>General EQ Discussion</a> <font color=#ffffff> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.240<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

